 the idea of allegory. In all these various ways, then, the real must be locked in opposition, to allow for the weight of little pleasures that are not merely renunciation, but also which allow us to talk about the actual in more detail.

The idea of the disguise is about the perception of health in the absence of a transcendent or impossible object, and similarly a vita contemplative might be neutral and contemplative in character. Thehuronian and satyrs are both anthropomorphised with a hint of humanity, and both with the past and both with a precarious course undone. 

